{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017Cht2mQYDG4K7Xb2LU8opu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup better:\n\n1. The StatefulSet uses `rabbitmq-erlang-cookie` secret with key `cookie` for the `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` env var.\n2. The data volume is `emptyDir` - so there's no persistent storage per node.\n3. The cookies found in the pods are completely different from both \"supersecretcookie\" and \"driftedcookie\" - meaning the actual `.erlang.cookie` files in the pods were somehow written differently.\n\nWait - the env var `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` comes from `rabbitmq-erlang-cookie` secret. \n\nBut looking at the actual cookies in each pod, they're all different from each other and from what I expected. The cluster status shows all three nodes running and clustered together, but with mismatched Erlang cookies, that shouldn't be possible - they wouldn't be able to communicate.\n\nI'm wondering if the `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` environment variable is being set, but since the pods use emptyDir volumes, RabbitMQ might be writing its own cookie file on startup. There could be a conflict between what the env var specifies and what's actually in the `.erlang.cookie` file. Also, I notice there's a separate `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` secret that doesn't seem to be referenced anywhere in the StatefulSet - that's odd. Hmm, but with `emptyDir` the cookie file gets wiped on each restart, so RabbitMQ should read from the env var every time. Let me check the rabbitmq.conf ConfigMap to see if there's something else controlling how the cookie is set or persisted.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2431,"cache_read_input_tokens":33027,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2431},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available