{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NsT7bY55NeZa8UCBCLGNM2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! From rabbitmq-2's perspective, all 3 nodes are also showing as running. So the current cluster status appears healthy from all nodes.\n\nLet me think about what's happening here:\n1. The `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` secret has different cookie for rabbitmq-2 (driftedcookie vs supersecretcookie)\n2. The actual `.erlang.cookie` files in the pods are all random and different from each other\n3. But the cluster_status from all nodes shows all 3 as running\n\nThe fact that rabbitmqctl cluster_status works from each node and shows all 3 running is contradictory to having different cookies. \nI'm realizing that when I run `rabbitmqctl` inside a container, it needs to authenticate to the local RabbitMQ node using the same cookie. If the command runs as root, it reads from `/root/.erlang.cookie`, but RabbitMQ itself runs as the rabbitmq user with its own cookie at `/var/lib/rabbitmq/.erlang.cookie`. These need to match for the command to work. Let me check what's actually in the root cookie file across these pods. Actually, stepping back—with the StatefulSet using emptyDir for data and Kubernetes peer discovery, when a pod restarts it loses its data and needs to rejoin the cluster.\n\nThe `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` environment variable is supposed to set the cookie, but I need to understand how the RabbitMQ Docker image entrypoint actually handles this. It likely generates a random cookie if the env var isn't set or the file doesn't exist yet, then writes it to `/var/lib/rabbitmq/.erlang.cookie`. If the file already exists, it reuses that one. But with emptyDir, the file gets wiped on restart.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the real issue might be that RabbitMQ doesn't write to the file at all when using the env var—it might use the cookie directly from memory. The file I'm reading could be something else entirely. But Erlang always reads from the `~/.erlang.cookie` file, so that doesn't make sense either.\n\nLet me check the actual entrypoint script to see what's happening during startup, and look at the pod logs to trace through the initialization sequence.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6089,"cache_read_input_tokens":38559,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6089},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"131d8a36-b175-44ff-986d-f38ae862e008","uuid":"77c90528-657f-4656-b9dd-d2a63963c465","request_id":"req_011CccZkCJuzMssrbK3rp3rh"}
