{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Lmu371Fj4ZehAWfkPKrKGS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So each node has a different cluster name. This confirms they are NOT actually in the same cluster - each node is running as its own separate single-node cluster. The `cluster_status` output is misleading because it shows all 3 in \"Disk Nodes\" and \"Running Nodes\", but this might just be reflecting what the K8s peer discovery found, not what's actually in the same Erlang cluster.\n\nAlso, `rabbitmqctl list_queues` on rabbitmq-0 timed out. This is a bad sign - it means there might be issues with the node's internal state.\n\nWait, actually it completed successfully but showed no queues? No, it said \"Timeout: 60.0 seconds ...\" which might just be a display thing, followed by \"Listing queues for vhost / ...\" which is the expected output header, then nothing (no queues in vhost /). \n\nThe queues might be in the /app vhost instead of the default one. But the real issue is clear now - each node thinks it's its own cluster, which is the root cause of the problem. I need to trace back through the timeline to understand how this happened, starting from when the StatefulSet was created.\n\nThe `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` secret stands out as suspicious since it assigns different cookies to different pods, but the StatefulSet doesn't even reference it. The K8s peer discovery mechanism should be finding other nodes during startup, but with emptyDir storage, each restart wipes the node state clean. Let me work through what likely happened when the nodes came up. are found and the first node alphabetically starts the cluster, with others joining it. But since emptyDir doesn't persist mnesia data, every pod restart looks like a fresh boot to the cluster discovery mechanism. Looking at those cookie file timestamps showing \"Jul 2 00:00\" while the pods started at 03:50 suggests the timestamp display might just be showing midnight as a default or the files were created earlier today.\n\nActually, emptyDir does persist across container restarts within a pod—it's only deleted when the pod itself is deleted. So if these pods were originally created at midnight with auto-generated cookies, and then the StatefulSet was updated around 03:50, the old cookies would still be sitting in the emptyDir from the earlier creation, which would explain the timestamp mismatch and the cluster joining behavior.\n\nThe real issue is that each pod has its own random Erlang cookie stored in its emptyDir, and when containers restart, they don't regenerate the cookie—they just reuse what's already there. This means all three pods end up with different cookies, preventing them from clustering together. The hint about `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` suggests this is exactly what happened, though I'm realizing that if the cookies were all different from the start, they wouldn't have clustered at midnight either. So they must have had the same cookie initially when they first started, and something changed to make them diverge. never actually set initially. The cookie file timestamps suggest the pods were created at midnight, when they wrote \"supersecretcookie\" and clustered successfully. Then someone modified the StatefulSet to inject per-pod cookie logic via a secret, causing rabbitmq-2 to get a different cookie on restart and lose cluster membership. At 03:50, the StatefulSet was reverted and all pods were restarted with fresh timestamps.\n\nBut if they all restarted fresh, they should all have the same cookie again and cluster properly—yet I'm seeing random cookies in the files, which doesn't add up. I need to step back and verify the actual state: are these three nodes in one cluster or separate clusters, and can they communicate with each other using rabbitmq tools?\n\nLooking at the cluster_status output more carefully, each node is reporting a different cluster name, which definitively means they're not clustered together. What's strange is that each one shows all three nodes as \"Running Nodes\"—if they were truly isolated single-node clusters, they should only list themselves. This suggests the Kubernetes peer discovery plugin might be reporting what it discovers through K8s endpoints rather than actual cluster membership. I should check the actual Erlang node connections directly to confirm what's really happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4006,"cache_read_input_tokens":48531,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4006},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"131d8a36-b175-44ff-986d-f38ae862e008","uuid":"c86d92c9-705e-4020-8c1a-dbba9e6233fa","request_id":"req_011CccZtCiSfiHGKbXd2tioM"}
