{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014Xuw5qwYJyBCsaBF3EztYM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting findings:\n\n1. **Erlang node connectivity**: All 3 nodes ARE connected to each other at the Erlang level. `nodes()` on each pod shows the other 2 nodes. Mnesia running_db_nodes shows all 3. So they ARE in the same Erlang cluster.\n\n2. **Cookie files**: \n   - All 3 cookie files have `Modify: 2026-07-02 00:00:00.000000000 +0000` (midnight)\n   - But `Birth` timestamps show:\n     - rabbitmq-0: 03:50:12 (just after the StatefulSet creation at 03:50:08)\n     - rabbitmq-1: 03:53:32\n     - rabbitmq-2: 03:53:54\n   \n   The files were created at their respective pod startup times, but someone explicitly set their modification timestamp to midnight. The Birth time confirms the file was newly created when each pod started, but the Modify timestamp being identical across all three at exactly midnight is definitely suspicious—the files were deliberately touched to reset their mtime.\n\nActually, this reveals something interesting: the files were created at pod startup with random content, but their modification times were artificially set to midnight. This is timestamp manipulation—either the adversary or some process is deliberately backdating these files to make them appear older than they actually are. Wait, but the pod ages show they were all created around 03:50 with zero restarts, so there shouldn't be any leftover emptyDir data from midnight. Yet the cookie file modification times are stamped at midnight—that's the real puzzle here. Could the modification times be getting set by something else, or is there another explanation I'm missing?\n\nLooking at the actual cookie values themselves: each node has a different random 20-character string, not the expected \"supersecretcookie\". Yet despite these mismatched cookies, all three nodes are somehow still connected at the Erlang level according to the nodes() output.\n\nWait—I think I've got it. The RabbitMQ startup process checks if the cookie file already exists. If it does, it keeps the existing value and ignores the `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` environment variable. But if the file doesn't exist, it writes the env var value to it. With an emptyDir volume, each fresh pod starts with no file, so \"supersecretcookie\" should get written initially.\n\nYet the files show random strings instead, all modified at midnight. This suggests something is overwriting the cookie files after RabbitMQ starts—either a sidecar, init container, or some other process. But there's no sidecar or init container visible in the StatefulSet definition, which is puzzling.\n\nWait, maybe I'm misinterpreting what I'm seeing. The `nodes()` output shows all three pods are connected to each other right now, which means they must be using matching cookies. So perhaps the random strings in the files aren't the actual cookies being used by the running Erlang VMs—maybe the RabbitMQ image reads the `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` env var and uses that directly without writing it back to the file, or it writes the env var value to the file but then something else overwrites it afterward. Why would all three nodes show the same environment variable but have different cookie files? The most plausible explanation is that the nodes started correctly with the shared cookie in memory, clustered together successfully, and then someone modified the cookie files on disk after the fact—possibly using timestamp manipulation to make the changes look older. Since the Erlang VMs keep the cookie in memory once they're running, the file modifications wouldn't affect their actual connectivity, which would explain why they're still clustered despite the disk files appearing different.\n\nBut if that's the case, restarting rabbitmq-2 should still work—it would read the environment variable again and write the correct cookie. Unless the adversary did something more sophisticated, like modifying the startup mechanism itself or the environment variable in a way that only affects certain nodes. to reconnect to the cluster and sync its state. Let me check if rabbitmq-2 is actually disconnected or lagging behind the others in terms of cluster membership or queue synchronization.\n\nI'm also realizing the core issue might be what happens on restart—the per-pod cookie secret would cause rabbitmq-2 to start with a different Erlang cookie than the rest of the cluster, preventing it from rejoining entirely.\n\nLet me trace through what resources are actually in play here. The `rabbitmq-setup` job completed successfully, so I need to understand what it configured and whether it's the mechanism that's injecting the mismatched cookie into the pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4210,"cache_read_input_tokens":52537,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4210},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"131d8a36-b175-44ff-986d-f38ae862e008","uuid":"a88eb588-4359-4263-b4db-cd97c37d9c76","request_id":"req_011CccZx9ezyDtCYyrv7V7J1"}
