{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KG7kWqU8WA64PmdAU8LCyV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clearer picture!\n\nFrom the StatefulSet events:\n- Created rabbitmq-0 at ~18m ago\n- Deleted rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 at ~16m ago\n- Created rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 at ~14m ago (x2 means it was created twice - once initially and once after deletion)\n\nSo the timeline is:\n1. T-18m: rabbitmq-0 created, rabbitmq-1 created, rabbitmq-2 created (initial setup)\n2. T-16m: rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 deleted by StatefulSet update\n3. T-14m: rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 recreated by StatefulSet update\n\nThe \"(x2 over 17m)\" notation indicates the pods were created twice within that window—once during initial setup and again after being deleted. Looking at the actual event timestamps, I see rabbitmq-0 was created 18m ago, then rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 were deleted 16m ago, followed by their recreation.\n\nThe critical detail from the logs is a WARNING message about the Erlang cookie: RabbitMQ is overriding the cookie file on disk because the value in the environment variable differs from what's stored on disk. Actually, I'm realizing the warning message is printed when the cookie file already exists with a different value than what's set in the environment variable—meaning the env var is overwriting the existing file. But if that's the case, the file should now contain the environment variable's value, yet I'm seeing a random 20-character string instead. This suggests either the env var is being used as the cookie without actually writing to the file, or the file was written after the message was logged, making those \"random\" values actually the truncated environment variable value.\n\nLooking at the RabbitMQ source code, when `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` is set, it reads the cookie from the environment and writes it to the cookie file, so the env var takes precedence.\n\nOn rabbitmq-2's startup, the file had some original value, but the environment variable `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE=supersecretcookie` overrode it, and RabbitMQ wrote \"supersecretcookie\" to the file. Yet the file now shows JSDQBCQINSEWTXEGHWJZ—which means the adversary must have overwritten the cookie file after RabbitMQ started, around the time they created `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` at 04:00. The cookie file must have been modified after RabbitMQ started, since the environment variable should have set it to \"supersecretcookie\" but it's showing JSDQBCQINSEWTXEGHWJZ instead. I've already verified the file contents directly, so something changed it after startup—either through the adversary's mechanism or another process, though there are no obvious sidecars or init containers that would do this.\n\nNow I'm noticing the `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` secret was created 10 minutes after startup, but there's no visible mechanism in the StatefulSet to actually use it. I should check for any CronJobs, DaemonSets, or other cluster-level resources that might be modifying the cookie files. Also, there's a `curl-test` pod running that isn't part of the standard RabbitMQ setup, and a completed `rabbitmq-setup` job—I need to investigate what those are doing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8030,"cache_read_input_tokens":66344,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":8030},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"131d8a36-b175-44ff-986d-f38ae862e008","uuid":"125d16f1-b667-4eb2-b585-e608ef4e1df7","request_id":"req_011CccaDAq7i1yx2N6uq5WvN"}
