{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VqhxuZRy9jUj5JQ7YXHaLs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All 3 nodes show the SAME cookie hash: `/5YjL0FZVT2rrwfvd+qYIQ==`\n\nThis is the MD5 hash of \"supersecretcookie\"! Let me verify:\n- `supersecretcookie` → base64(md5(\"supersecretcookie\")) = `/5YjL0FZVT2rrwfvd+qYIQ==`\n\nSo ALL 3 nodes are running with cookie hash `/5YjL0FZVT2rrwfvd+qYIQ==` = the hash of \"supersecretcookie\". They all have the same cookie.\nThe cookie files on disk show different random strings because the RabbitMQ entrypoint initially wrote \"supersecretcookie\" to them, but then something modified those files afterward with random values. However, the Erlang VM already loaded the cookie into memory at startup, so all three nodes are still using \"supersecretcookie\" internally even though the disk files have been tampered with.\n\nThe \"Overriding Erlang cookie\" message appeared on every pod at startup, which means each one had a different cookie value in its file initially—including rabbitmq-0, even though its emptyDir was freshly created. This suggests the adversary mechanism was using a per-pod cookie secret through an init container that read different cookie values for each pod before the main startup process ran. The `RABBITMQ_ERLANG_COOKIE` environment variable might always trigger this warning whenever it's set, regardless of whether a conflicting file exists—it could just be RabbitMQ's way of noting that the env var is taking precedence. Looking at how the Docker entrypoint handles this, it probably writes the cookie file from the env var unconditionally, and logs a warning if an existing file had a different value, but I need to verify whether the warning fires in all cases or only on conflicts. rote the file with random values, but the running Erlang VM still had the original cookie in memory. When RabbitMQ restarts, the Docker entrypoint would rewrite the same value, yet I'm seeing these unusual 20-character uppercase strings in the file instead. Let me check if those random values are actually MD5 hashes of \"supersecretcookie\" by comparing against the base64-encoded hash from the logs.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7195,"cache_read_input_tokens":78730,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7195},"output_tokens":17,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"131d8a36-b175-44ff-986d-f38ae862e008","uuid":"bd21535b-3572-431f-b76b-186e2a87b550","request_id":"req_011CccaPmyk51ytmKn6oKA7R"}
